This is the last reel of the series, and it is the feature that gives Scala its distinctive flavor: contextual abstraction. It answers a simple question. What if the compiler could fill in some arguments for you, the ones that are obvious from context, so you never have to write them by hand? In Scala 2 this lived under one heavily overloaded keyword, implicit. Scala 3 broke that single idea into a few clear pieces, and those pieces are what we will walk through.

Start with the core mechanism, shown in the diagram. Somewhere there is a call site that needs a value, but you do not pass it. Instead the compiler searches what is called the given scope, the set of contextual values currently in view. If it finds exactly one that fits, it injects that value for you, and all of this happens at compile time. There is no reflection, no runtime lookup, no magic at execution. By the time your program runs, the argument has already been written in for you.

Now the two halves of that mechanism, in code. A given is a value you mark as available for the compiler to supply. Here we declare a given greeting of type String equal to the word Hello. That puts a String into the given scope. On the other side, a method asks for one using the using keyword. The greet method takes a name, and then a second parameter list marked using g of type String. That using is the method saying: I need a String from context, please find it. So when you call greet of Ada, you pass only the name. The compiler sees the using slot, looks in scope, finds your greeting, and injects it, producing Hello, Ada. You never wrote the second argument.

That mechanism becomes powerful when you build a type class on top of it, and this is the ad-hoc polymorphism the type-system reel pointed ahead to. Remember the contrast. Generics give you parametric polymorphism: one body that works for every type, blind to the specifics. Type classes give you the opposite kind of flexibility: behavior defined per type, added from the outside, without ever touching the type itself.

Look at the code. First we declare a trait Show of A with a single method, show, that turns an A into a String. That trait is the capability we want certain types to have. Next we provide an instance for Int: a given Show of Int, whose show wraps the number, producing text like Int and the value. Now the key method. Log takes a value of some type A, and a using parameter of type Show of A. It is not asking the value to inherit anything; it is asking context to supply evidence that A knows how to be shown. Call log of forty-two, and the compiler finds your Show of Int instance, hands it over, and you get back Int forty-two. The beautiful part is that you can give a type these abilities even if you do not own its source code. A library type, a built-in type, anything: you just provide a given instance, and it joins the type class.

The last piece smooths over the syntax, and it is extension methods. Often you wish a type you do not own simply had one more method. The extension keyword lets you add one. Here we write extension on a String parameter s, and define shout as s converted to upper case with an exclamation mark added. From then on you can write the string hello, dot shout, and get back HELLO with a bang, exactly as though String had always carried that method. No wrapper class, no inheritance.

Extensions pair naturally with type classes to give you clean call sites. We write a generic extension on any value a of type A, defining a show method that takes a using Show of A and calls it. Now you can write forty-two dot show, and behind that tidy syntax the compiler is finding the given, supplying it, and running your type class instance. The capability lives outside the type, but the call reads as if it lived inside.

So that completes the picture, and the series. Given and using are the engine: values the compiler supplies, slots that ask for them, resolved at compile time. Type classes use that engine to grant behavior to types from the outside, the ad-hoc counterpart to generics. And extension methods make all of it read like the methods were there from the start. Together they are how Scala lets you abstract over context itself.
